hijack /ˈhaɪˌdʒæk/

(hijacking,hijacked,hijacks) 

1. V-T If someone hijacks a plane or other vehicle, they illegally take control of it by force while it is travelling from one place to another. 劫持 

例： Two men tried to hijack a plane on a flight from Riga to Murmansk. 两名男子试图劫持一架从里加飞往摩尔曼斯克的飞机。 

2. N-COUNT Hijack is also a noun. 劫持 

例： Every minute during the hijack seemed like a week. 劫持过程中，每一分钟都像一个星期似的。 

3. hijacking N-COUNT 劫持 

例： Car hijackings are running at a rate of nearly 50 a day. 平均每天发生50起劫车事件。 

4. V-T If you say that someone has hijacked something, you disapprove of the way in which they have taken control of it when they had no right to do so. 强行控制 [表不满] 

例： A peaceful demonstration had been hijacked by anarchists intent on causing trouble. 一场和平示威已被一心想制造事端的无政府主义分子强行控制了。

